Day 06 - Windows Service Creation Detection
Objective

Simulate the creation of a Windows service and investigate how Wazuh detects system changes associated with the activity.

This exercise demonstrates how attackers can use Windows services to establish persistence and maintain access to a compromised system.

Lab Environment
Infrastructure
Windows 10 Pro Endpoint
Ubuntu 22.04 Wazuh Server
Kali Linux VM
VirtualBox Lab Environment
Components
Wazuh Manager
Wazuh Indexer
Wazuh Dashboard
Wazuh Windows Agent
Scenario

Attackers frequently create Windows services after obtaining administrative privileges.

Services can be configured to start automatically during system boot and execute code with elevated privileges.

The purpose of this exercise was to simulate service creation and investigate how Wazuh detects the resulting system modifications.

MITRE ATT&CK Mapping
T1112 - Modify Registry

Tactic

Defense Evasion

Description

Adversaries may modify the Windows Registry to store configuration data, maintain persistence, or alter system behavior.

Lab Relevance

Creating a Windows service generated new registry entries under:

HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\TestService

Wazuh detected the registry modification and mapped the activity to MITRE ATT&CK technique T1112.

Activity Performed
Service Creation

The following command was executed from an elevated Command Prompt:

sc create TestService binPath= "C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe"

Result:

[SC] CreateService SUCCESS

The service was successfully created and registered within Windows.

Detection Workflow

Windows Endpoint

↓

Windows Registry Modified

↓

Wazuh Agent

